WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.938
RICK SMOLAN: Thank you.

00:00:00.938 --> 00:00:01.438
Thank you.

00:00:04.115 --> 00:00:05.490
MEI-MEI ZHAO: All
right, welcome.

00:00:05.490 --> 00:00:09.830
So to start, I think
I speak for myself

00:00:09.830 --> 00:00:12.500
and many people in
the audience when

00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:17.930
I say being a professional
photographer is very cool.

00:00:17.930 --> 00:00:21.160
And I've definitely thought
that being a National Geographic

00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:23.140
photographer and going
and chasing adventure

00:00:23.140 --> 00:00:25.720
and action is just
something so unbelievable.

00:00:25.720 --> 00:00:30.350
So how did you first become
interested in photography,

00:00:30.350 --> 00:00:34.007
and how did you later decide
to turn it into a career?

00:00:34.007 --> 00:00:36.340
RICK SMOLAN: I think that
probably my answer is probably

00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:38.930
very similar to almost
any other, at least

00:00:38.930 --> 00:00:41.380
male, photographer
you ask, which

00:00:41.380 --> 00:00:43.685
is I was painfully
shy when I was a kid.

00:00:43.685 --> 00:00:45.435
And my dad gave me a
camera when I was 14.

00:00:45.435 --> 00:00:47.768
It was the first time I could
go over and talk to girls.

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:50.020
Seriously.

00:00:50.020 --> 00:00:51.832
I mean, every
photographer I know,

00:00:51.832 --> 00:00:53.540
even the ones that
are the most outgoing,

00:00:53.540 --> 00:00:55.010
are kind of shy underneath.

00:00:55.010 --> 00:00:57.390
And it was just a great excuse.

00:00:57.390 --> 00:01:00.150
It also allowed me to
transition from group to group.

00:01:00.849 --> 00:01:02.390
Well, when I was
growing up, I always

00:01:02.390 --> 00:01:04.515
thought that most people
had a gene that taught you

00:01:04.515 --> 00:01:07.054
how to talk to strangers and
it was left out of my kit

00:01:07.054 --> 00:01:07.720
when I was born.

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:09.678
And I thought if I watched
other people enough,

00:01:09.678 --> 00:01:11.110
I could learn how to do it.

00:01:11.110 --> 00:01:13.150
So being a photographer,
it's sort of be-there,

00:01:13.150 --> 00:01:14.060
but-not-be-there.

00:01:14.060 --> 00:01:17.150
So I can hang out with the jocks
or the nerds or the freaks.

00:01:17.150 --> 00:01:19.720
Or I could move in and
out of different groups,

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:21.780
and everybody
accepted me because I

00:01:21.780 --> 00:01:23.100
tended to make them look good.

00:01:24.597 --> 00:01:25.930
And I never studied photography.

00:01:25.930 --> 00:01:27.590
It was my hobby.

00:01:27.590 --> 00:01:30.552
My dad was adamant about me
not being a photographer when

00:01:30.552 --> 00:01:32.260
I told him I wanted
to be a photographer.

00:01:32.260 --> 00:01:34.176
When I grew up, I didn't
know what that meant,

00:01:34.176 --> 00:01:37.059
but he wouldn't let
me go to a college

00:01:37.059 --> 00:01:38.600
where they had a
photography program.

00:01:39.777 --> 00:01:41.860
He said, I'm not going to
pay for you go to school

00:01:41.860 --> 00:01:44.270
and end up doing wedding
pictures and baby portraits.

00:01:44.270 --> 00:01:46.780
I want you to be a doctor or
a lawyer or some serious job.

00:01:46.780 --> 00:01:47.880
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Don't
listen to your parents.

00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:48.960
See how wrong they were?

00:01:50.250 --> 00:01:53.160
RICK SMOLAN: So I did the
yearbook in high school

00:01:53.160 --> 00:01:56.020
and in the newspaper, and
I just loved photography.

00:01:56.020 --> 00:01:56.999
It was just fun.

00:01:56.999 --> 00:01:58.290
MEI-MEI ZHAO: That's fantastic.

00:01:58.290 --> 00:02:01.530
So do you remember what was
your first major assignment when

00:02:01.530 --> 00:02:04.100
you were like, oh man,
this could actually

00:02:04.100 --> 00:02:06.300
be something I want
to do with my life?

00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:08.360
RICK SMOLAN: A
friend of mine-- I

00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:10.832
used to read "Popular
Photography."

00:02:10.832 --> 00:02:13.040
Back then, it was really
the equivalent to the blogs.

00:02:13.040 --> 00:02:15.980
And a friend of mine
in college one day

00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:19.296
read that "Life"
magazine was doing

00:02:19.296 --> 00:02:20.670
"One Day in the
Life of America."

00:02:20.670 --> 00:02:23.349
And he bet me $25.

00:02:23.349 --> 00:02:25.640
He thought I was a much better
photographer than I did.

00:02:25.640 --> 00:02:27.145
I was always very insecure.

00:02:27.145 --> 00:02:28.440
I still am.

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:31.430
And he bet me that I could
get hired by Life magazine.

00:02:31.430 --> 00:02:33.550
So I took a train
to New York City.

00:02:33.550 --> 00:02:35.000
I was in Pennsylvania.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.400
And I had my yearbook
and a box of pictures.

00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:39.470
I had no appointment.

00:02:39.470 --> 00:02:41.300
I just show up at the
Time Life building,

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:44.537
and I'm dressed in jeans
and sneakers and a t-shirt.

00:02:44.537 --> 00:02:46.870
And I go to the reception
desk, and the woman says, yes,

00:02:46.870 --> 00:02:47.495
can I help you?

00:02:47.495 --> 00:02:50.540
And I said, I'm here to see
the editor of "Life" magazine.

00:02:50.540 --> 00:02:52.520
And she goes, do you
have appointment?

00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:53.761
I said, no.

00:02:53.761 --> 00:02:55.760
I read about this issue
that you guys are doing.

00:02:55.760 --> 00:02:56.960
And she said, well,
you can't just

00:02:56.960 --> 00:02:57.975
show up here without
an appointment.

00:02:57.975 --> 00:02:58.620
I'm sorry.

00:02:58.620 --> 00:03:01.100
And she waves me
out of the building.

00:03:01.100 --> 00:03:02.700
And I'm walking out
of the building,

00:03:02.700 --> 00:03:06.680
and there's all these guys
walking in jeans and t-shirts

00:03:06.680 --> 00:03:10.180
bringing packages wrapped up
in brown paper with string.

00:03:10.180 --> 00:03:11.740
So I had this sort
of crazy idea.

00:03:11.740 --> 00:03:14.609
So I went around to Sam
Flax, wrapped up my yearbook

00:03:14.609 --> 00:03:16.650
in paper and string, and
then followed these guys

00:03:16.650 --> 00:03:19.029
into the freight elevator
and got up to the floor.

00:03:19.029 --> 00:03:21.570
And, of course, when I got out
and then went to the reception

00:03:21.570 --> 00:03:24.600
desk, the woman there said,
well, who's the package for?

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:27.390
I said, well, no, actually, I'm
here to see the photo editor.

00:03:27.390 --> 00:03:28.060
As she said--

00:03:28.060 --> 00:03:28.970
MEI-MEI ZHAO: It
might be illegal,

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:30.020
but at least it
got you in there.

00:03:30.020 --> 00:03:31.990
RICK SMOLAN: So she got
really angry and she said,

00:03:31.990 --> 00:03:32.920
you have to get out of here.

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:34.128
So I go back to the elevator.

00:03:34.128 --> 00:03:36.055
I remember I push
the Down button.

00:03:36.055 --> 00:03:36.930
I was standing there.

00:03:36.930 --> 00:03:38.620
I was thinking,
what would the hero

00:03:38.620 --> 00:03:40.060
do in a movie at
this moment, like

00:03:40.060 --> 00:03:41.784
if you're writing
this as a movie?

00:03:41.784 --> 00:03:43.950
And I thought, this woman
works for "Life" magazine,

00:03:43.950 --> 00:03:45.650
and she probably never
gets to see the pictures

00:03:45.650 --> 00:03:46.483
until they come out.

00:03:46.483 --> 00:03:48.670
I had this thing
about "Life" magazine.

00:03:48.670 --> 00:03:50.540
If you were the secretary,
all your friends

00:03:50.540 --> 00:03:52.248
would say it's so cool
to work at "Life,"

00:03:52.248 --> 00:03:54.070
but she probably
doesn't see anything.

00:03:54.070 --> 00:03:55.195
So I thought, I'll go back.

00:03:55.195 --> 00:03:57.153
I'll just show her two
of my favorite pictures.

00:03:57.153 --> 00:03:59.600
She'll kick me out, but at
least I'll feel like I tried.

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:01.420
So I went back to her desk.

00:04:01.420 --> 00:04:02.252
She's on the phone.

00:04:02.252 --> 00:04:04.210
And I get that look like,
what the hell are you

00:04:04.210 --> 00:04:04.876
doing back here?

00:04:04.876 --> 00:04:06.456
But she's talking to somebody.

00:04:06.456 --> 00:04:07.830
And I'm standing
there trying not

00:04:07.830 --> 00:04:09.550
to make eye contact, because
I know if I look at her,

00:04:09.550 --> 00:04:11.125
she's going to go,
get out of here.

00:04:11.125 --> 00:04:13.000
And some guy walks out
of one of the offices,

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:15.541
and I'm looking down trying not
to make eye contact with her.

00:04:15.541 --> 00:04:16.500
And this guy walks out.

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:18.749
I remember looking down, and
he had jeans and sneakers

00:04:18.749 --> 00:04:19.279
on like me.

00:04:19.279 --> 00:04:21.440
So I figured he was
also not important.

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:24.527
And he said, hey
kid, what are those?

00:04:24.527 --> 00:04:26.360
And I had these pictures,
and I was shaking.

00:04:26.360 --> 00:04:28.360
I was so nervous, because
the more this went on,

00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:30.350
the more I'm just
feeling terrible.

00:04:30.350 --> 00:04:32.382
And I said, oh, just
some of my pictures.

00:04:32.382 --> 00:04:33.340
He goes, can I see the?

00:04:33.340 --> 00:04:34.298
And I said, yeah, sure.

00:04:34.298 --> 00:04:37.035
And he looked through then and
he said, these are really good.

00:04:37.035 --> 00:04:38.410
He said, what are
you doing here?

00:04:38.410 --> 00:04:39.575
And I just sort of lost it.

00:04:39.575 --> 00:04:43.390
I said, I came all the way
from my college and nobody

00:04:43.390 --> 00:04:44.896
will talk to me and
all I want to do

00:04:44.896 --> 00:04:46.520
is just show my
pictures to the editor.

00:04:46.520 --> 00:04:47.478
He said, OK, calm down.

00:04:47.478 --> 00:04:48.160
Calm down.

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:51.130
He said, I'm Grey Villet.

00:04:51.130 --> 00:04:53.247
I'm the senior photographer
here at "Life,"

00:04:53.247 --> 00:04:54.580
and I really like your pictures.

00:04:54.580 --> 00:04:56.538
And if you wait a minute,
I'll go back and talk

00:04:56.538 --> 00:04:59.290
to John Loengard, the
director of photography,

00:04:59.290 --> 00:05:01.430
and I'll see if he can see you.

00:05:01.430 --> 00:05:03.534
This woman gets off the
phone, and I've just

00:05:03.534 --> 00:05:05.575
done what she's paid not
to allow ever to happen.

00:05:06.940 --> 00:05:09.320
And so he comes back
out, and he said, John.

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:11.320
I thought he was going
to say, he can't see you,

00:05:11.320 --> 00:05:11.903
but thank you.

00:05:11.903 --> 00:05:13.830
And he said, John's really busy.

00:05:13.830 --> 00:05:16.026
And he said, if you
don't mind waiting,

00:05:16.026 --> 00:05:17.150
it might be an hour or two.

00:05:17.150 --> 00:05:18.608
It's like, I'll
sleep on the couch.

00:05:19.611 --> 00:05:20.360
I'll wait all day.

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:21.880
It was not inconvenient.

00:05:21.880 --> 00:05:24.100
So about an hour
later, he comes out.

00:05:24.100 --> 00:05:26.552
And this guy comes out and
say, hi, I'm John Loengard.

00:05:26.552 --> 00:05:27.510
Come back in my office.

00:05:27.510 --> 00:05:29.906
And he said, what do you got?

00:05:29.906 --> 00:05:32.030
So I showed him my yearbook,
and I had some prints.

00:05:32.030 --> 00:05:33.160
I'm thinking, really?

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:34.540
I mean, I brought my yearbook?

00:05:34.540 --> 00:05:36.870
I couldn't have even
done a portfolio?

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:39.219
And he goes through and he
says, these are pretty good.

00:05:39.219 --> 00:05:40.635
He said, so what
can I do for you?

00:05:40.635 --> 00:05:42.170
And I said, well,
I saw that you're

00:05:42.170 --> 00:05:44.490
going to do this "One Day
in the Life of America."

00:05:44.490 --> 00:05:48.500
And I said, I was hoping maybe
you'd might like to hire me?

00:05:48.500 --> 00:05:50.400
And he said, well, you
know, we've already

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:52.310
hired 99 photographers,
and the whole concept

00:05:52.310 --> 00:05:53.737
is 99 photographers one day.

00:05:53.737 --> 00:05:56.195
He said, why don't you take
some pictures and send them in?

00:05:56.195 --> 00:05:58.225
And I remember taking
this deep breath

00:05:58.225 --> 00:06:01.065
and I said, Mr. Loengard, my
whole life growing up I've

00:06:01.065 --> 00:06:04.105
been reading "Life" magazine,
and I would just do anything

00:06:04.105 --> 00:06:06.605
if I could really be part of
the team, like, to be official.

00:06:07.670 --> 00:06:10.360
And I thought I'd
blown it, because he

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:11.950
had no expression
on his face at all.

00:06:11.950 --> 00:06:13.990
And he just sat there
and he just stared at me.

00:06:13.990 --> 00:06:16.790
And I remember I was
dripping with sweat,

00:06:16.790 --> 00:06:18.600
and he's just staring at me.

00:06:18.600 --> 00:06:21.430
Then I see a little smile
in the corner of his mouth.

00:06:21.430 --> 00:06:23.830
He goes, well, I guess
it wouldn't financially

00:06:23.830 --> 00:06:26.410
bankrupt Time Life if we
made it 100 instead of 99.

00:06:26.410 --> 00:06:28.710
He said, OK, you're hired.

00:06:28.710 --> 00:06:31.149
So that was my first job.

00:06:31.149 --> 00:06:32.940
And I photographed two
of my friends taking

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:34.570
a shower together at college.

00:06:34.570 --> 00:06:38.776
And her father turned out
to be a Baptist minister.

00:06:38.776 --> 00:06:40.150
And this was the
picture everyone

00:06:40.150 --> 00:06:43.580
talked about, because kids naked
in college-- what a concept,

00:06:43.580 --> 00:06:44.620
right?

00:06:44.620 --> 00:06:46.189
But it was the one
picture everybody

00:06:46.189 --> 00:06:47.730
talked about when
the issue came out.

00:06:47.730 --> 00:06:50.480
So then I met the
people at "Time,"

00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:51.920
and suddenly I had a job.

00:06:51.920 --> 00:06:53.450
And I'd never
studied photography,

00:06:53.450 --> 00:06:56.360
so I'm glad my friend
bet me the $25.

00:06:56.967 --> 00:06:58.300
MEI-MEI ZHAO: That's incredible.

00:06:58.300 --> 00:07:00.580
So I think a lot of
us here can relate,

00:07:00.580 --> 00:07:02.785
because the Google job
interview process is--

00:07:02.785 --> 00:07:03.784
RICK SMOLAN: I've heard.

00:07:03.784 --> 00:07:04.678
It's the gauntlet.

00:07:06.020 --> 00:07:07.950
MEI-MEI ZHAO: But it
seems like you also

00:07:07.950 --> 00:07:09.420
went through quite
the interview,

00:07:09.420 --> 00:07:11.560
but we're really
glad you got the job.

00:07:11.560 --> 00:07:16.570
So I watched your TED Talk.

00:07:16.570 --> 00:07:22.930
And so one of the projects
that you chose to pursue

00:07:22.930 --> 00:07:27.105
is documenting
Amerasian children.

00:07:27.355 --> 00:07:29.230
RICK SMOLAN: For those
of you who don't know,

00:07:29.230 --> 00:07:33.580
Amerasian children are American
fathers and Asian mothers,

00:07:33.580 --> 00:07:36.330
which happens wherever we
have troops in the world.

00:07:36.330 --> 00:07:39.030
Nothing to do with being at
war, but wherever we have bases,

00:07:39.030 --> 00:07:43.720
there are children being born
as a result of these bases.

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:45.680
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Yeah, so
if you guys have time,

00:07:45.680 --> 00:07:47.180
if you have or
haven't watched, it's

00:07:47.180 --> 00:07:49.010
a really incredible TED Talk.

00:07:49.010 --> 00:07:51.360
Do you mind giving us a
little bit more details

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:54.120
about that project
in particular?

00:07:54.120 --> 00:07:55.920
RICK SMOLAN: I'll
try to do it quickly,

00:07:55.920 --> 00:08:00.310
because as a photographer,
I had trouble staying

00:08:00.310 --> 00:08:02.240
outside of the things
I'm photographing.

00:08:02.240 --> 00:08:04.390
I tend to get very
emotionally involved

00:08:04.390 --> 00:08:05.360
in the stories I shoot.

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:08.050
And I think all of
us, as photographers,

00:08:08.050 --> 00:08:10.850
hope that we're not
just documenting things,

00:08:10.850 --> 00:08:12.430
but maybe our pictures
could actually

00:08:12.430 --> 00:08:13.900
have an effect on
people's lives.

00:08:13.900 --> 00:08:16.170
I mean, I think that's the
dream of every photojournalist.

00:08:16.170 --> 00:08:18.211
I also want to say that
there's a real difference

00:08:18.211 --> 00:08:20.290
between paparazzi,
fashion photographers, war

00:08:20.290 --> 00:08:21.817
photographers, photojournalists.

00:08:21.817 --> 00:08:23.650
Because they have a
camera around their neck

00:08:23.650 --> 00:08:25.040
doesn't mean they're
all interchangeable.

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:26.480
And there's certain
code of ethics

00:08:26.480 --> 00:08:28.561
and certain
emotional things that

00:08:28.561 --> 00:08:30.435
go along with different
kinds of photography.

00:08:30.435 --> 00:08:32.760
And I love being
a photojournalist,

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:35.226
because I think journalist is
the part of it is you're not

00:08:35.226 --> 00:08:36.850
just taking pictures,
but you're trying

00:08:36.850 --> 00:08:39.527
to shine a light on
something and some injustice.

00:08:39.527 --> 00:08:42.110
You hope that your pictures may
actually touch somebody's life

00:08:42.110 --> 00:08:43.240
or change them.

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:47.830
So I found out that there
were 40,000 children who

00:08:47.830 --> 00:08:51.670
have fathered by GIs
all over Southeast Asia.

00:08:51.670 --> 00:08:54.984
And in many of these
countries, the children,

00:08:54.984 --> 00:08:56.650
by the local governments,
are considered

00:08:56.650 --> 00:08:58.059
to be children of Americans.

00:08:58.059 --> 00:08:59.600
And the American
government considers

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:02.840
these to be the children
of prostitutes or whatever.

00:09:04.110 --> 00:09:07.230
These kids are stuck in this
horrible diplomatic limbo,

00:09:07.230 --> 00:09:09.110
and through no fault of
their own, obviously.

00:09:09.110 --> 00:09:10.380
But they're prejudiced against.

00:09:10.380 --> 00:09:11.129
They're beaten up.

00:09:11.129 --> 00:09:12.240
They're made fun of.

00:09:12.240 --> 00:09:14.620
All of us growing up,
somebody would make fun of us

00:09:14.620 --> 00:09:16.310
because we had a big
nose or big ears.

00:09:16.310 --> 00:09:18.760
You would imagine, from
your earliest memories,

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:26.290
people ridiculing you simply
because of the reason that you

00:09:26.290 --> 00:09:27.160
came to be.

00:09:27.160 --> 00:09:29.470
So I thought, at
the beginning, this

00:09:29.470 --> 00:09:32.230
was the bad GIs getting
the poor girls pregnant

00:09:32.230 --> 00:09:33.410
and leaving them.

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:35.749
But when I actually when out
and started spending time,

00:09:35.749 --> 00:09:37.540
I found that everybody
was using everybody.

00:09:37.540 --> 00:09:39.270
The GIs wanted to
get laid, right?

00:09:39.270 --> 00:09:41.529
And the girls, in
some cases, wanted

00:09:41.529 --> 00:09:43.570
to get pregnant, because
their families had said,

00:09:43.570 --> 00:09:45.740
if the guy marries you
and takes you to American,

00:09:45.740 --> 00:09:47.300
then we can all come.

00:09:47.300 --> 00:09:51.190
And so all I cared about were
these poor kids, because I just

00:09:51.190 --> 00:09:54.830
thought, as a kid that was
really shy and made fun of,

00:09:54.830 --> 00:09:57.070
I could really identify with
a lot of these children.

00:09:59.119 --> 00:10:00.910
It was a three-day
story for Time Magazine,

00:10:00.910 --> 00:10:02.830
but I got so
disturbed by it that I

00:10:02.830 --> 00:10:04.830
decided I would take
six months off and find

00:10:04.830 --> 00:10:06.010
six kids in different
countries and go

00:10:06.010 --> 00:10:07.343
back and forth amongst the kids.

00:10:07.343 --> 00:10:09.710
And my fantasy was that the
story would get published,

00:10:09.710 --> 00:10:12.335
and I would send a copy of it to
every congressman and senator,

00:10:12.335 --> 00:10:16.280
and people would do so outraged
that something would happen.

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:18.030
I couldn't find a
single American magazine

00:10:18.030 --> 00:10:19.113
that would tell the story.

00:10:19.930 --> 00:10:20.430
What?

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:22.160
Illegitimate children
of American GIs?

00:10:22.160 --> 00:10:23.240
Forget it.

00:10:23.240 --> 00:10:24.170
We're not going there.

00:10:24.170 --> 00:10:25.590
I mean, nobody would publish it.

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:27.239
I finally found a
German magazine.

00:10:27.239 --> 00:10:28.780
And at the last
minute, they ended up

00:10:28.780 --> 00:10:30.820
pulling all the strongest
pictures, because they

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:33.070
were worried it was going
to offend their advertisers.

00:10:33.459 --> 00:10:35.000
So in the middle of
doing this story,

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:36.416
I met this one
little girl who was

00:10:36.416 --> 00:10:38.250
unlike all the other children.

00:10:38.250 --> 00:10:41.520
She was not cowed by this.

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:43.040
She didn't seem to be haunted.

00:10:43.040 --> 00:10:44.450
In fact, she was popular.

00:10:44.450 --> 00:10:47.160
She was the most American of
any kids that I photographed.

00:10:47.160 --> 00:10:51.506
And long story short, in the
course of photographing her,

00:10:51.506 --> 00:10:53.469
her grandmother,
who had raised her

00:10:53.469 --> 00:10:55.260
and had done a wonderful
job of raising her

00:10:55.260 --> 00:10:58.860
in this little village up
along the DMZ in South Korea

00:10:58.860 --> 00:11:00.604
but near North Korea--
the grandmother

00:11:00.604 --> 00:11:02.020
died and left her
to me in a will.

00:11:02.020 --> 00:11:03.799
I was 28 years
old, and suddenly I

00:11:03.799 --> 00:11:05.840
had this 11-year-old that
looked American, didn't

00:11:05.840 --> 00:11:07.280
speak a word of English.

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:10.580
And I won't tell you the whole
story, but it's on ted.com.

00:11:10.580 --> 00:11:13.312
And it's exciting to
think that a million

00:11:13.312 --> 00:11:14.270
people have watched it.

00:11:14.270 --> 00:11:16.670
And she's sort of like
my kid sister now.

00:11:16.670 --> 00:11:21.340
And our children-- the strangest
part is my kids are 12 and 14,

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:23.550
and her kids are seven and nine.

00:11:23.550 --> 00:11:25.920
So our children have
sleepovers together now.

00:11:25.920 --> 00:11:29.450
And part of my brain still
can't quite get around that.

00:11:29.450 --> 00:11:31.490
I still think of her as
this 11-year-old girl.

00:11:31.490 --> 00:11:35.302
And she is more mature and
smarter and wiser than me,

00:11:35.302 --> 00:11:37.010
and she has been since
the day I met her.

00:11:37.010 --> 00:11:39.047
And I've given you the
CliffsNotes version

00:11:39.047 --> 00:11:41.380
of the story, but when you
see the pictures of this girl

00:11:41.380 --> 00:11:43.300
and you see her
story and how she's

00:11:43.300 --> 00:11:44.985
touched other people's lives.

00:11:44.985 --> 00:11:46.830
And I've never
published the story.

00:11:46.830 --> 00:11:48.330
I just decided the
best gift I could

00:11:48.330 --> 00:11:50.390
give her is to put
the pictures in a box

00:11:50.390 --> 00:11:51.590
and put them in the closet.

00:11:51.590 --> 00:11:53.390
And now that her
daughter's almost 11,

00:11:53.390 --> 00:11:56.850
which is the age that I met
her at, she's been saying,

00:11:56.850 --> 00:11:57.966
why don't we do a book?

00:11:57.966 --> 00:11:59.340
It would be fun
to do a book now,

00:11:59.340 --> 00:12:01.470
because it's sort
of like full circle.

00:12:01.470 --> 00:12:05.410
So I think Natasha's story and
now this new movie, "Tracks"--

00:12:05.410 --> 00:12:07.921
both are labors of love for me.

00:12:07.921 --> 00:12:10.420
They're both things that I got
very emotionally involved in.

00:12:10.420 --> 00:12:12.295
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Yeah, it
would be great to have

00:12:12.295 --> 00:12:14.030
Natasha come in a TED Talk.

00:12:14.030 --> 00:12:15.650
She seems to be
quite the young lady.

00:12:15.650 --> 00:12:16.150
It'll be--

00:12:16.150 --> 00:12:18.566
RICK SMOLAN: She's
so poised and funny.

00:12:18.566 --> 00:12:20.430
MEI-MEI ZHAO: She
is, and it's amazing

00:12:20.430 --> 00:12:21.850
how you're able
to capture so much

00:12:21.850 --> 00:12:23.270
of her character in your photos.

00:12:23.270 --> 00:12:24.760
And it would be
great to follow up

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:27.552
with her to see what
she's up to these days.

00:12:27.552 --> 00:12:29.650
RICK SMOLAN: You know what
I thought would be fun?

00:12:29.650 --> 00:12:31.316
I realize that we
have very little time,

00:12:31.316 --> 00:12:33.370
and thank you all
so much for coming.

00:12:33.370 --> 00:12:36.020
I was wondering if we jumped
to the trailer for "Tracks"?

00:12:36.020 --> 00:12:37.130
It's a two-minute trailer.

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:37.740
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Yeah, of course.

00:12:37.740 --> 00:12:39.989
RICK SMOLAN: Mei-Mei, can I
set it up just one second?

00:12:40.519 --> 00:12:41.310
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Yeah.

00:12:41.310 --> 00:12:43.200
So yeah.

00:12:44.260 --> 00:12:50.480
So Rick has also been working on
a book for the movie "Tracks."

00:12:50.480 --> 00:12:52.660
So "Tracks" is a movie
that-- you know what?

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:54.450
I'm just going to
let Rick tell you.

00:12:55.640 --> 00:12:59.340
But it's about Rick's
journey through Australia.

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:02.557
And it originally was a
book made into a movie.

00:13:02.557 --> 00:13:04.515
And now Rick is writing
a book about the movie.

00:13:04.515 --> 00:13:06.030
RICK SMOLAN: And about
the original trip.

00:13:06.030 --> 00:13:08.530
It's sort of one of those--
what is it?-- the Russian dolls.

00:13:09.437 --> 00:13:11.770
MEI-MEI ZHAO: [INAUDIBLE],
but it was quite interesting.

00:13:11.770 --> 00:13:12.120
So yeah.

00:13:12.120 --> 00:13:14.620
So please give us a little
description about the project.

00:13:14.620 --> 00:13:16.786
RICK SMOLAN: So I'll set
it up really quickly, which

00:13:16.786 --> 00:13:19.230
is before the Natasha story,
before the Amerasian story,

00:13:19.230 --> 00:13:21.354
"Time Magazine" sent me to
the Outback of Australia

00:13:21.354 --> 00:13:23.281
to do a cover story
on Aborigines.

00:13:23.281 --> 00:13:24.780
And there was a
woman I've been told

00:13:24.780 --> 00:13:26.600
to contact who was
a social worker that

00:13:26.600 --> 00:13:28.641
worked with Aborigines to
take me into the campus

00:13:28.641 --> 00:13:29.550
to get permission.

00:13:29.550 --> 00:13:32.850
And so I checked into
my hotel, and the woman

00:13:32.850 --> 00:13:34.880
who I had hired-- I
hadn't met her yet,

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:36.270
but she lived down the street.

00:13:36.270 --> 00:13:37.500
I meet her down the street.

00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:38.950
I walked into my
hotel, and I looked up,

00:13:38.950 --> 00:13:41.158
and the most beautiful woman
I'd ever seen in my life

00:13:41.158 --> 00:13:42.970
is washing the
windows of my hotel.

00:13:42.970 --> 00:13:43.942
And I was 20 years old.

00:13:43.942 --> 00:13:45.400
I had three cameras
around my neck.

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:48.310
And I took some pictures of
her, and she got really angry

00:13:48.310 --> 00:13:50.560
and started yelling at me
to put my damn cameras down,

00:13:50.560 --> 00:13:51.601
and who the hell are you?

00:13:51.601 --> 00:13:53.580
And so I walked
over and apologized,

00:13:53.580 --> 00:13:56.250
but I couldn't really
calm her down, so I left.

00:13:56.250 --> 00:13:58.090
And I shot pictures
of Aborigines all day

00:13:58.090 --> 00:14:00.532
with this woman who
took me to the camps.

00:14:00.532 --> 00:14:02.490
And the woman working
for me said, what are you

00:14:02.490 --> 00:14:03.330
doing for dinner tonight?

00:14:03.330 --> 00:14:05.290
I said, I'm going to go
back and work on captions.

00:14:05.290 --> 00:14:07.740
And she said, well, a group of
us that work with Aborigines

00:14:07.740 --> 00:14:09.330
are having dinner
at a friend's house.

00:14:09.330 --> 00:14:11.050
Would you like to come and
meet some other people involved

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:12.900
in the aboriginal
community and movement?

00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:15.572
So I went to this house
on the outside of town,

00:14:15.572 --> 00:14:17.780
and it was falling down and
the walls were crumbling.

00:14:17.780 --> 00:14:19.154
There was no roof,
and I thought,

00:14:19.154 --> 00:14:20.900
this can't be the right address.

00:14:20.900 --> 00:14:22.580
And I knocked on the
door, and of course

00:14:22.580 --> 00:14:24.190
who opens the door
but the woman who'd

00:14:24.190 --> 00:14:26.155
been watching the
windows of my hotel

00:14:26.155 --> 00:14:29.194
who was not happy to see me and
told me to put my cameras down.

00:14:29.194 --> 00:14:30.610
I couldn't photograph
her friends.

00:14:30.610 --> 00:14:31.790
It's like, OK.

00:14:31.790 --> 00:14:34.440
So I walk in and she's got
camels tied up in the backyard.

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:36.350
And I said, why do
you have camels?

00:14:36.350 --> 00:14:37.829
And she wouldn't tell me.

00:14:37.829 --> 00:14:39.370
So I went to the
woman working for me

00:14:39.370 --> 00:14:41.630
and said, why does
your friend have camels

00:14:41.630 --> 00:14:43.434
and why is she so mean?

00:14:43.434 --> 00:14:45.600
Sorry I took a picture of
her, but I didn't actually

00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:46.890
kill anybody or anything.

00:14:47.996 --> 00:14:49.620
And she said, oh,
Robyn's going to walk

00:14:49.620 --> 00:14:51.890
2,000 miles across the
Outback of Australia

00:14:51.890 --> 00:14:54.450
from here through the desert
out to the Indian Ocean.

00:14:54.450 --> 00:14:55.330
And said, why?

00:14:55.330 --> 00:14:57.200
And she said, we
don't know, and we

00:14:57.200 --> 00:14:59.060
want to go because we're afraid
she's going to die out there.

00:14:59.060 --> 00:15:00.893
She won't let any of
us come, and we're just

00:15:00.893 --> 00:15:02.757
terrified that she's
going to disappear.

00:15:02.757 --> 00:15:05.090
So anyway, during the week,
I kept meeting these people.

00:15:05.090 --> 00:15:07.734
At the end of the week,
the woman working for me--

00:15:07.734 --> 00:15:08.775
it was my last day there.

00:15:08.775 --> 00:15:11.400
And she said, Robin
wants to ask you a favor,

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:13.942
but she's been kind of mean to
you and now she's embarrassed.

00:15:13.942 --> 00:15:15.149
And I said, what's the favor?

00:15:15.149 --> 00:15:17.966
I thought maybe she wants copies
of my pictures or something.

00:15:17.966 --> 00:15:20.590
And she said, well, she wrote to
National Geographic a year ago

00:15:20.590 --> 00:15:22.715
and asked if they would
give her money so she could

00:15:22.715 --> 00:15:24.750
buy the saddles and
the special equipment

00:15:24.750 --> 00:15:26.560
that she needs to
survive out there,

00:15:26.560 --> 00:15:27.784
and they never even answered.

00:15:27.784 --> 00:15:29.700
And she thought maybe
you might know somebody,

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:31.600
if she could use your
name, because she doesn't

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:33.849
want to spend another year
washing windows and waiting

00:15:33.849 --> 00:15:35.660
on idiots in pubs.

00:15:35.660 --> 00:15:38.380
And I said, well, I've met some
of the editors at workshops.

00:15:38.380 --> 00:15:41.570
I mean, working for National
Geographic was something when

00:15:41.570 --> 00:15:44.630
I'm 90 years old,
if you're lucky.

00:15:44.630 --> 00:15:47.120
So I said sure, thinking
that would be the end of it.

00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:49.050
I went back to New
York and I got a call

00:15:49.050 --> 00:15:51.100
a week later from the editor
of National Geographic, who

00:15:51.100 --> 00:15:52.870
said that they'd gotten
a letter from this woman.

00:15:52.870 --> 00:15:53.840
It sounded interesting.

00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:56.140
They were thinking
of funding her trip.

00:15:56.140 --> 00:15:57.149
But was she a nut case?

00:15:57.149 --> 00:15:58.440
Was she going to die out there?

00:15:58.440 --> 00:16:01.140
Because they didn't want
"National Geographic-funded

00:16:01.140 --> 00:16:03.456
explorer dies on week two."

00:16:03.456 --> 00:16:04.955
And I said, well,
she's very intent.

00:16:04.955 --> 00:16:05.746
She's very serious.

00:16:05.746 --> 00:16:06.780
I've seen her maps.

00:16:06.780 --> 00:16:07.657
I've seen the camels.

00:16:07.657 --> 00:16:09.990
And he said, well, since you
guys are such good friends,

00:16:09.990 --> 00:16:12.239
would you like to be the
photographer that we send out

00:16:12.239 --> 00:16:15.350
to find her along the way?

00:16:15.350 --> 00:16:17.495
So anyway, if we can
jump to the trailer.

00:16:18.750 --> 00:16:21.390
This is a movie, which opened
last week all over the United

00:16:21.390 --> 00:16:22.760
States.

00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:26.762
Mia Wasikowska, this wonderful
actress, just-- it's so eerie.

00:16:26.762 --> 00:16:28.220
I'll show you some
of the pictures,

00:16:28.220 --> 00:16:31.140
but she looks exactly like
Robyn did during this trip.

00:16:31.140 --> 00:16:33.430
And it's produced
by the same people

00:16:33.430 --> 00:16:34.910
who did "The King's Speech."

00:16:34.910 --> 00:16:37.390
And they're already talking
Oscar nominations for Mia.

00:16:37.390 --> 00:16:39.350
So can we roll that?

00:16:39.350 --> 00:16:40.120
OK, here we go.

00:16:40.120 --> 00:16:42.383
Maybe bring the lights down
on us a little bit here.

00:16:42.383 --> 00:16:43.049
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:16:43.049 --> 00:16:45.400
- --walk across the Australian
desert from Alice Springs

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:50.340
to the Indian Ocean, a
distance of 2,000 miles.

00:16:50.340 --> 00:16:52.890
When people ask me why I'm
doing it, my usual answer is,

00:16:52.890 --> 00:16:53.390
why not?

00:16:57.980 --> 00:16:59.810
-Your plan is ridiculous.

00:17:01.098 --> 00:17:03.235
-Why don't you just
show them the trip?

00:17:03.235 --> 00:17:04.464
Talina will come to you.

00:17:05.336 --> 00:17:06.544
-I just want to be by myself.

00:17:12.031 --> 00:17:14.080
-You must be mad, girly.

00:17:14.080 --> 00:17:17.819
You know, that's about 2,000
miles, six months of hard walk.

00:17:19.019 --> 00:17:20.760
-You want to die out
there or something?

00:17:22.251 --> 00:17:24.736
[INSPIRATIONAL MUSIC]

00:17:48.095 --> 00:17:49.089
-Leave me alone.

00:17:59.526 --> 00:18:00.520
Go away!

00:18:02.508 --> 00:18:03.999
