00:18:34.360 --> 00:18:35.734
RICK SMOLAN: The
cinematographer,

00:18:35.734 --> 00:18:39.830
a woman named Mandy Walker,
she did most incredible job

00:18:39.830 --> 00:18:42.235
of capturing what it
felt like out there--

00:18:42.235 --> 00:18:44.610
what the lake was
like, the dust.

00:18:44.610 --> 00:18:47.620
Mia gives this amazing, very
understated performance,

00:18:47.620 --> 00:18:50.040
where she says very little
and she communicate so much

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:50.680
in the film.

00:18:50.680 --> 00:18:52.720
It was so eerie sitting
in the movie theater,

00:18:52.720 --> 00:18:54.816
as you can probably
imagine, watching

00:18:54.816 --> 00:18:56.940
literally my photographs
come to life, because they

00:18:56.940 --> 00:18:59.231
took a lot of the pictures
and actually built the sets.

00:18:59.985 --> 00:19:02.360
Actually, maybe if you could
jump to some of the pictures

00:19:02.360 --> 00:19:04.002
while we're talking,
It would be fun.

00:19:04.002 --> 00:19:05.460
I'll show you some
of the pictures.

00:19:05.460 --> 00:19:06.640
And you see the real Robyn.

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:11.054
You see Mia back and forth,
and it's just really eerie.

00:19:11.054 --> 00:19:12.720
MEI-MEI ZHAO: I got
to ask, what does it

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:14.632
feel like to see yourself
portrayed on film?

00:19:14.632 --> 00:19:15.840
And did you pick Adam Driver?

00:19:15.840 --> 00:19:17.658
RICK SMOLAN: No, no,
they chose that one.

00:19:17.658 --> 00:19:18.930
MEI-MEI ZHAO: They
chose that one?

00:19:18.930 --> 00:19:19.470
RICK SMOLAN: He's great.

00:19:19.470 --> 00:19:21.710
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Did you
feel like he portrayed you

00:19:21.710 --> 00:19:23.190
in an accurate manner?

00:19:23.190 --> 00:19:27.240
I can't imagine watching
someone play me on a big screen.

00:19:27.240 --> 00:19:29.680
So how does that feel?

00:19:29.680 --> 00:19:31.530
RICK SMOLAN: It was
very odd and eerie.

00:19:31.530 --> 00:19:33.610
My brother is a
director in Hollywood

00:19:33.610 --> 00:19:36.670
and said, look, you need
to realize that they're

00:19:36.670 --> 00:19:39.349
going to-- those of you
who are into movies--

00:19:39.349 --> 00:19:41.390
the arc of the character,
you have to start here.

00:19:41.390 --> 00:19:43.190
And in real life, most
people don't change.

00:19:43.190 --> 00:19:45.439
But in movies, everybody
starts here and ends up here.

00:19:45.439 --> 00:19:47.310
So he said, basically,
they're going

00:19:47.310 --> 00:19:50.100
to make you the irritating pest
at the beginning of the movie.

00:19:50.100 --> 00:19:53.090
And then as you go on hopefully
by the end of the movie,

00:19:53.090 --> 00:19:54.410
you redeem yourself.

00:19:54.410 --> 00:19:56.136
And that was pretty
much what they did.

00:19:56.136 --> 00:19:57.510
I mean, I think
they exaggerated.

00:19:58.411 --> 00:20:00.160
As I said, I'm not a
fashion photographer.

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:03.360
And, of course, they had him
posing me and say, turn left.

00:20:03.360 --> 00:20:03.860
Turn right.

00:20:03.860 --> 00:20:04.850
Move your shoulders like this.

00:20:04.850 --> 00:20:07.530
Which that would be like a "New
York Times" reporter making up

00:20:07.530 --> 00:20:08.700
a quote.

00:20:08.700 --> 00:20:09.960
But I'm fine with it.

00:20:09.960 --> 00:20:11.820
I mean, I think the
director, John Curran,

00:20:11.820 --> 00:20:13.170
did a wonderful job.

00:20:13.170 --> 00:20:16.030
And we're doing a new book,
which is this book here.

00:20:18.200 --> 00:20:19.240
I got to go back.

00:20:19.240 --> 00:20:20.987
I shot tens of
thousands of photographs

00:20:20.987 --> 00:20:21.820
during Robyn's trip.

00:20:21.820 --> 00:20:23.880
And even though
National Geographic

00:20:23.880 --> 00:20:25.840
did this-- where is it?

00:20:25.840 --> 00:20:26.644
It's buried here.

00:20:26.644 --> 00:20:27.560
So this was the cover.

00:20:28.522 --> 00:20:29.480
You can be Vanna White.

00:20:29.480 --> 00:20:31.438
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Now, this
was the original cover.

00:20:33.972 --> 00:20:36.430
RICK SMOLAN: So even though
they did a 32-page cover story,

00:20:36.430 --> 00:20:40.450
which for any photographer,
32 pages is just unbelievable.

00:20:40.450 --> 00:20:43.150
But I shot literally tens
of thousands of pictures.

00:20:43.150 --> 00:20:45.770
And it's almost like
which of your children

00:20:45.770 --> 00:20:46.880
make it into the lifeboat?

00:20:46.880 --> 00:20:48.338
You have to choose
just-- you know?

00:20:48.338 --> 00:20:50.270
So that's Robyn on
the left with her dog,

00:20:50.270 --> 00:20:52.407
Diggity, and that's
Mia on the right.

00:20:52.407 --> 00:20:53.990
They even put here
in the same blouse.

00:20:53.990 --> 00:20:55.920
They went and manufactured
the same clothes

00:20:55.920 --> 00:20:57.720
that we wore back then.

00:20:57.720 --> 00:20:59.570
If you go to the next
picture, I sort of put

00:20:59.570 --> 00:21:00.660
a lot of comparisons.

00:21:00.660 --> 00:21:02.189
That's us on the left.

00:21:02.189 --> 00:21:03.730
And that's Mia and
Adam on the right.

00:21:04.907 --> 00:21:06.740
I don't know why they
felt it was necessary,

00:21:06.740 --> 00:21:09.190
why they wanted to have
the actors look like us

00:21:09.190 --> 00:21:11.370
or wear our clothes,
but it was kind of cool.

00:21:13.650 --> 00:21:16.210
I mean, who would know the
difference other than you

00:21:16.210 --> 00:21:17.500
now that we've kind of met?

00:21:17.500 --> 00:21:20.720
But, I mean, it doesn't change
the entertainment value of it.

00:21:20.720 --> 00:21:25.050
If you go to the next picture,
he's a little taller than me.

00:21:26.660 --> 00:21:28.565
Roby's still gorgeous
as she was back then.

00:21:28.565 --> 00:21:30.690
Actually at the end of the
movie it's kind of cool,

00:21:30.690 --> 00:21:33.892
because they show-- at the very
end of the movie, Mia swims

00:21:33.892 --> 00:21:35.350
underwater and the
credits come up,

00:21:35.350 --> 00:21:36.960
and they go to the
original pictures

00:21:36.960 --> 00:21:38.470
in National Geographic.

00:21:38.470 --> 00:21:41.100
I've seen the movie quite a few
times now at film festivals.

00:21:41.100 --> 00:21:43.340
And you hear people in the
audience go, oh my god,

00:21:43.340 --> 00:21:43.881
that's right.

00:21:43.881 --> 00:21:45.270
This actually happened.

00:21:45.270 --> 00:21:47.270
Because you going in it's
based on a real story,

00:21:47.270 --> 00:21:50.780
but when you actually see the
real Robyn and the real camels,

00:21:50.780 --> 00:21:52.612
it makes the story
even more touching.

00:21:52.612 --> 00:21:54.320
Can I share something
with your audience?

00:21:54.320 --> 00:21:55.570
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Yeah, of course.

00:21:55.570 --> 00:21:57.170
RICK SMOLAN: I'm a
technology junkie.

00:21:58.264 --> 00:21:59.930
So many of our books
have done something

00:21:59.930 --> 00:22:02.600
like-- we were the first ones
ever to put a CD-ROM in a book.

00:22:02.600 --> 00:22:04.900
It seems like a long time ago.

00:22:04.900 --> 00:22:06.610
We were the first
people to ever do

00:22:06.610 --> 00:22:09.740
a mass-customized best seller,
where every copy of "America

00:22:09.740 --> 00:22:12.197
24/7" you could upload
your own photographs,

00:22:12.197 --> 00:22:13.780
and you were on the
cover of our book,

00:22:13.780 --> 00:22:15.488
but it was a "New York
Times" bestseller.

00:22:15.488 --> 00:22:18.190
So this new book combines a
number of different things.

00:22:18.190 --> 00:22:20.700
So first of all, it's really,
I think, kind of cool.

00:22:20.700 --> 00:22:23.730
Pictures from Robyn's
original journey.

00:22:23.730 --> 00:22:25.222
And this is a big wide book.

00:22:25.222 --> 00:22:27.430
We're actually doing a
Kickstarter campaign right now

00:22:27.430 --> 00:22:27.930
for this.

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:30.980
And so the first part
of it is actually

00:22:30.980 --> 00:22:32.990
taking you through
her original journey.

00:22:32.990 --> 00:22:34.390
She wrote a book
called "Tracks,"

00:22:34.390 --> 00:22:36.510
which is why the
movie's called "Tracks,"

00:22:36.510 --> 00:22:39.222
and she sold a million
copies in 18 languages.

00:22:39.222 --> 00:22:40.680
But I'll show you
the coolest part,

00:22:40.680 --> 00:22:44.640
which is that we have an app,
if can find the page here.

00:22:44.640 --> 00:22:46.810
There's a free app you can
download called Aurasma.

00:22:46.810 --> 00:22:48.630
It's made by HP.

00:22:48.630 --> 00:22:50.049
And so throughout
the book, we've

00:22:50.049 --> 00:22:51.590
done something kind
of cool-- I think

00:22:51.590 --> 00:22:54.320
it's cool-- which
is you simply point

00:22:54.320 --> 00:22:55.950
your phone at photographs.

00:22:55.950 --> 00:22:59.990
There's a little picture of a
little icon of a phone here.

00:22:59.990 --> 00:23:02.540
And this works on
Android or iOS.

00:23:02.540 --> 00:23:03.055
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Would it be
easier if I helped you hold it?

00:23:03.055 --> 00:23:03.470
RICK SMOLAN: Yeah.

00:23:03.470 --> 00:23:04.428
OK, so you can do that.

00:23:05.480 --> 00:23:10.183
And then all I do is point
my phone at that photograph.

00:23:10.183 --> 00:23:12.480
Let's see if I'm getting
good Wi-Fi in here.

00:23:13.505 --> 00:23:14.380
Let's see.

00:23:14.380 --> 00:23:15.200
Is it working?

00:23:15.200 --> 00:23:17.270
I'm probably not getting
good signal here.

00:23:18.780 --> 00:23:20.360
There we go.

00:23:20.360 --> 00:23:22.539
And now it's playing
that scene in the movie.

00:23:22.539 --> 00:23:25.080
So this is the scene of Robyn
writing to National Geographic.

00:23:25.080 --> 00:23:26.997
Well, it's Mia writing
to National Geographic.

00:23:26.997 --> 00:23:28.413
And so throughout
the whole book--

00:23:28.413 --> 00:23:29.176
[RINGTONE CHIMING]

00:23:29.176 --> 00:23:29.884
--you get to see.

00:23:29.884 --> 00:23:30.627
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:30.627 --> 00:23:32.085
MEI-MEI ZHAO:
Perfect time to call.

00:23:32.085 --> 00:23:33.267
RICK SMOLAN: It's probably
Harvey Weinstein saying,

00:23:33.267 --> 00:23:34.201
you can't do that.

00:23:36.070 --> 00:23:38.430
So it's really kind of fun
to see the original Robyn

00:23:38.430 --> 00:23:40.610
in the book, and then you
to see that scene as it

00:23:40.610 --> 00:23:41.740
came to life in the movie.

00:23:41.740 --> 00:23:46.617
And then-- I can do this
part-- so halfway-- sorry?

00:23:46.617 --> 00:23:48.450
AUDIENCE: Were you the
first one to do this?

00:23:48.450 --> 00:23:48.900
RICK SMOLAN: I think so.

00:23:48.900 --> 00:23:49.530
I've never seen this done.

00:23:49.530 --> 00:23:50.240
Before.

00:23:50.240 --> 00:23:51.920
HP uses it for advertising.

00:23:51.920 --> 00:23:54.630
So like in a magazine,
you point at a sneaker,

00:23:54.630 --> 00:23:56.660
and then you can
rotate the sneaker.

00:23:56.660 --> 00:23:59.270
But I think using this
in an editorial context

00:23:59.270 --> 00:24:00.530
is really cool.

00:24:00.530 --> 00:24:02.850
We did this actually last
year in "The Human Face

00:24:02.850 --> 00:24:05.876
of Big Data," which
Google was a sponsor of.

00:24:05.876 --> 00:24:08.250
And you could actually point
to different people in here.

00:24:08.250 --> 00:24:10.370
They would give you their
TED Talk, basically.

00:24:10.370 --> 00:24:12.590
So the still image--
what's so cool about it

00:24:12.590 --> 00:24:14.640
is if I point to a
picture-- so here.

00:24:14.640 --> 00:24:15.890
You'll get a kick out of this.

00:24:15.890 --> 00:24:20.200
Here's National Geographic
from 1978, right?

00:24:20.200 --> 00:24:21.590
Let me find this picture.

00:24:21.590 --> 00:24:24.770
There's a picture Robyn sitting
by the campfire learning

00:24:24.770 --> 00:24:27.210
to speak aboriginal dialects.

00:24:27.210 --> 00:24:28.470
So this is the original copy.

00:24:28.470 --> 00:24:30.230
Nothing's been done to it.

00:24:30.230 --> 00:24:31.360
And I'll show you.

00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:36.420
It actually works on an issue of
National Geographic from 1978.

00:24:36.420 --> 00:24:37.170
People said, wait.

00:24:37.170 --> 00:24:40.100
How did you embed something
in the picture in 1978?

00:24:40.100 --> 00:24:41.120
And I didn't.

00:24:41.120 --> 00:24:43.020
Let's see if this works.

00:24:43.020 --> 00:24:43.520
OK.

00:24:45.750 --> 00:24:47.250
So this is the scene of Adam.

00:24:47.250 --> 00:24:48.760
This is Robyn by
the fire at night.

00:24:48.760 --> 00:24:50.887
This is Adam and Mia
by the fire at night.

00:24:50.887 --> 00:24:52.845
So it's actually like a
fingerprint technology.

00:24:52.845 --> 00:24:56.106
It actually recognizes the
picture as a unique pattern.

00:24:56.106 --> 00:24:57.730
And anywhere it sees
that, whether it's

00:24:57.730 --> 00:25:02.210
a poster, on the internet, even
a fuzzy black and white picture

00:25:02.210 --> 00:25:04.820
in a magazine, it'll trigger
that video, which is so cool.

00:25:04.820 --> 00:25:06.040
MEI-MEI ZHAO: That's amazing.

00:25:06.040 --> 00:25:06.650
RICK SMOLAN: The
fact that you can

00:25:06.650 --> 00:25:09.625
do this with an old National
Geographic is just so freaky.

00:25:09.625 --> 00:25:10.385
MEI-MEI ZHAO: That's incredible.

00:25:10.385 --> 00:25:12.460
RICK SMOLAN: The Kickstarter
campaign that we're doing

00:25:12.460 --> 00:25:13.960
is-- people said,
well, can't I just

00:25:13.960 --> 00:25:16.580
buy this eventually on
Amazon if you get funded?

00:25:16.580 --> 00:25:17.730
And the answer is yes.

00:25:17.730 --> 00:25:21.040
But one of the
rewards is you get

00:25:21.040 --> 00:25:23.030
a copy of the original
National Geographic

00:25:23.030 --> 00:25:24.770
together with the book.

00:25:24.770 --> 00:25:26.470
We've also got
prints from the book.

00:25:26.470 --> 00:25:27.610
Anyway, I'm not
trying to sell you,

00:25:27.610 --> 00:25:29.776
but if you're looking for
a cool gift for somebody--

00:25:29.776 --> 00:25:32.767
But the second half of the
book is actually the movie.

00:25:32.767 --> 00:25:33.850
So let me go back to that.

00:25:35.010 --> 00:25:36.370
So these are now images.

00:25:36.370 --> 00:25:39.890
The filmmakers allowed me to go
into the movie footage itself

00:25:39.890 --> 00:25:42.069
and actually take still
frames out of the movie.

00:25:42.069 --> 00:25:44.110
And this woman, Mandy
Walker, the cinematographer

00:25:44.110 --> 00:25:45.544
I mentioned, was so good.

00:25:45.544 --> 00:25:47.210
So I went through the
movie at one frame

00:25:47.210 --> 00:25:49.600
a second on my
MacBook Air and found

00:25:49.600 --> 00:25:51.690
images that looked
like still photographs

00:25:51.690 --> 00:25:53.140
that a photojournalist
would take,

00:25:53.140 --> 00:25:55.056
and then we associated
the screenplay with it.

00:25:55.056 --> 00:25:56.520
So you get to meet
the real Robin.

00:25:56.520 --> 00:25:59.130
Then you go back and you see
this is the campfire scene.

00:26:01.290 --> 00:26:03.090
This is six color
printing spot varnish.

00:26:03.090 --> 00:26:04.260
I couldn't find
anybody to publish it.

00:26:04.260 --> 00:26:05.551
I went to all these publishers.

00:26:05.551 --> 00:26:08.210
I mean, I've done pretty well
as a publisher over the years.

00:26:08.210 --> 00:26:09.959
But they all said, oh,
it's too expensive.

00:26:09.959 --> 00:26:11.510
What if the movie
doesn't do well?

00:26:11.510 --> 00:26:12.950
I said, I want
six-color printing,

00:26:12.950 --> 00:26:15.060
thick matte paper, spot varnish.

00:26:15.060 --> 00:26:16.810
So my friends say, do
it as a Kickstarter.

00:26:16.810 --> 00:26:18.935
And there's so many people
that love Robyn's story.

00:26:18.935 --> 00:26:20.160
It's so inspiring.

00:26:20.160 --> 00:26:21.630
And there's sort
of a mystery to it

00:26:21.630 --> 00:26:23.705
also, which is that the
question is probably

00:26:23.705 --> 00:26:25.830
the first question each of
you has is, why on earth

00:26:25.830 --> 00:26:28.210
would somebody do this?

00:26:28.210 --> 00:26:32.062
And I always think of
it like the Mona Lisa.

00:26:32.062 --> 00:26:33.770
If we knew why the
Mona Lisa was smiling,

00:26:33.770 --> 00:26:35.690
we wouldn't be talking
about the Mona Lisa.

00:26:35.690 --> 00:26:38.680
And she didn't do
this purposely.

00:26:38.680 --> 00:26:41.340
But I think it's a very
complicated answer of what

00:26:41.340 --> 00:26:43.900
drove her to let go of society.

00:26:43.900 --> 00:26:44.830
Imagine no GPS.

00:26:45.920 --> 00:26:46.570
No phones.

00:26:46.570 --> 00:26:47.530
No satellites.

00:26:47.530 --> 00:26:49.940
I made her take a Flying
Doctor radio, which

00:26:49.940 --> 00:26:51.480
is the one time she needed it.

00:26:51.480 --> 00:26:52.500
It didn't work.

00:26:52.500 --> 00:26:54.357
She was attacked by wild camels.

00:26:54.357 --> 00:26:56.690
She said, sometimes on the
map, she'd come up to a place

00:26:56.690 --> 00:26:58.106
where it would
show one road going

00:26:58.106 --> 00:27:00.979
to the right, like a path, a
dirt road, and one to the left.

00:27:00.979 --> 00:27:02.895
And she'd get there and
there'd be five roads.

00:27:03.900 --> 00:27:05.589
Because since the
maps were done,

00:27:05.589 --> 00:27:07.130
farmers would be
out there, ranchers.

00:27:07.130 --> 00:27:09.350
People were just
basically driven so far

00:27:09.350 --> 00:27:11.684
in this one direction, it
would become another road.

00:27:11.684 --> 00:27:14.100
And she said on the map it
says, take the road on the left

00:27:14.100 --> 00:27:16.680
and there'll be a well
two weeks along that road.

00:27:16.680 --> 00:27:19.449
And she'd be walking
for two weeks going,

00:27:19.449 --> 00:27:20.490
what if I took the wrong?

00:27:21.570 --> 00:27:23.100
So she did right out of water.

00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:25.610
I mean, it's an amazing
story how she survived.

00:27:25.610 --> 00:27:27.275
And it isn't just luck.

00:27:27.275 --> 00:27:29.220
I mean, so many of
the ways that she

00:27:29.220 --> 00:27:31.750
solved your problems
were just so clever.

00:27:31.750 --> 00:27:37.650
There's a scene in the movie
where she is with her dog

00:27:37.650 --> 00:27:39.244
and she gets
separated the camel.

00:27:39.244 --> 00:27:40.910
She's lost and she
goes back to find it.

00:27:40.910 --> 00:27:42.880
And she finds the
thing that she's loss.

00:27:42.880 --> 00:27:45.030
And then she turns around
and can't figure out

00:27:45.030 --> 00:27:46.870
where she left the camels.

00:27:46.870 --> 00:27:49.530
And she didn't take any
water, and she's with her dog,

00:27:49.530 --> 00:27:51.380
and she's totally
freaking out and trying

00:27:51.380 --> 00:27:52.810
to figure out what to do.

00:27:52.810 --> 00:27:55.744
And I'm not going to
ruin it, but if you

00:27:55.744 --> 00:27:57.160
want to see a movie
that you can't

00:27:57.160 --> 00:28:00.000
stop thinking about afterwards,
it's playing at the Angelica

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:03.451
down here and at the Lincoln
Plaza Cinemas uptown.

00:28:03.451 --> 00:28:05.200
But there's so many
things like that movie

00:28:05.200 --> 00:28:08.450
where you see the fierce
intelligence of this woman.

00:28:08.450 --> 00:28:10.210
And she's one of the
few people I've ever

00:28:10.210 --> 00:28:13.410
met in my life who-- most of
us spend our lives avoiding

00:28:13.410 --> 00:28:15.074
the things that frighten us.

00:28:15.074 --> 00:28:17.240
And sometimes this negative
center of gravity-- it's

00:28:17.240 --> 00:28:18.199
always pushing it away.

00:28:18.199 --> 00:28:19.990
And I think she's the
only person I've ever

00:28:19.990 --> 00:28:21.790
met that actually goes
towards the things

00:28:21.790 --> 00:28:24.730
not in a masochistic
way but to see it as,

00:28:24.730 --> 00:28:26.920
is that really worthy of
my spending my whole life

00:28:26.920 --> 00:28:28.620
not doing something?

00:28:28.620 --> 00:28:31.190
So I've never met anybody that
actually challenges themselves

00:28:31.190 --> 00:28:31.731
all the time.

00:28:31.731 --> 00:28:33.630
I was very inspired
spending time with her.

00:28:33.630 --> 00:28:34.838
MEI-MEI ZHAO: That's amazing.

00:28:34.838 --> 00:28:36.960
And she sounds incredible
and so does this film.

00:28:36.960 --> 00:28:39.850
But how did you
feel about the trip,

00:28:39.850 --> 00:28:42.300
especially now looking
retrospectively?

00:28:42.300 --> 00:28:44.090
Was it as more difficult
and challenging

00:28:44.090 --> 00:28:45.690
than you had expected?

00:28:45.690 --> 00:28:47.450
RICK SMOLAN: I wasn't
even a Boy Scout.

00:28:47.450 --> 00:28:49.645
So my friends said, you're
the ones getting back out

00:28:49.645 --> 00:28:50.036
there, not her.

00:28:50.036 --> 00:28:51.120
At least she's been
preparing for this.

00:28:51.120 --> 00:28:52.680
MEI-MEI ZHAO: So, I'm going
to say, you did the trip too,

00:28:52.680 --> 00:28:52.900
yeah.

00:28:52.900 --> 00:28:53.790
You did the trip too.

00:28:53.790 --> 00:28:55.800
RICK SMOLAN: I mean, I
had a four-wheel drive,

00:28:55.800 --> 00:28:59.260
air-conditioned car, listening
to Jackson Browne in my care.

00:28:59.260 --> 00:29:01.010
I'm really digging myself here.

00:29:05.770 --> 00:29:08.510
I was 28 at the time, but
emotionally, I was about 19.

00:29:08.510 --> 00:29:10.480
So every girlfriend
I'd had lasted a week,

00:29:10.480 --> 00:29:14.350
and I'd get an assignment and it
never worked through anything.

00:29:14.350 --> 00:29:17.487
And Robyn was one of these
people that would challenge.

00:29:17.487 --> 00:29:19.320
There were just ways
she challenged herself.

00:29:19.320 --> 00:29:21.230
She was always challenging me.

00:29:21.230 --> 00:29:24.854
I remember earlier on the trip
on day one of the first times

00:29:24.854 --> 00:29:27.020
I went out with her, we
were sitting around talking.

00:29:27.020 --> 00:29:28.790
And she said, when
are you get here?

00:29:28.790 --> 00:29:29.760
And I said, what?

00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:32.010
And she'd been out there
about too much at that point.

00:29:32.010 --> 00:29:33.510
And she said, when are
you going to get here?

00:29:33.510 --> 00:29:34.970
And I thought, oh,
she'd gone nuts.

00:29:34.970 --> 00:29:37.110
I mean, being out
there alone that much,

00:29:37.110 --> 00:29:39.010
you get a little crazy.

00:29:39.010 --> 00:29:41.670
And I said, Robyn, I'm sitting
right here in front of you.

00:29:41.670 --> 00:29:43.070
I just couldn't imagine
what she was talking about.

00:29:43.070 --> 00:29:44.650
And she said, no, you're not.

00:29:44.650 --> 00:29:46.700
She said, since you
got here a day ago,

00:29:46.700 --> 00:29:49.050
you've been talking about
your Time cover story

00:29:49.050 --> 00:29:52.810
for Taiwan, where you're going
to leave the car in two weeks.

00:29:52.810 --> 00:29:55.210
It's like you come out
here and you're everywhere

00:29:55.210 --> 00:29:56.000
except with me.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:57.420
It's like if you're going to
come out here, damn it, then

00:29:57.420 --> 00:29:57.920
be here.

00:29:57.920 --> 00:29:59.639
But don't spend the
whole time with me

00:29:59.639 --> 00:30:01.180
planning what you're
going to do next

00:30:01.180 --> 00:30:03.040
or thinking about what
you should done yesterday.

00:30:03.040 --> 00:30:04.930
And it was one of those
things where somebody

00:30:04.930 --> 00:30:07.560
goes like that to you, and
you kind of go, you know what?

00:30:07.560 --> 00:30:08.560
You're absolutely right.

00:30:08.560 --> 00:30:11.000
I mean, so many of us
spend our time in the past

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:12.810
or in the future and
never where we are.

00:30:13.612 --> 00:30:15.320
I kept saying to her
throughout the trip,

00:30:15.320 --> 00:30:16.530
you've got to keep a journal?

00:30:16.530 --> 00:30:17.390
I mean, someday
you're going to want

00:30:17.390 --> 00:30:18.515
to write a book about this.

00:30:18.515 --> 00:30:22.086
And she said, why do you have to
turn everything into a product?

00:30:22.086 --> 00:30:23.960
Like, why can't you
experience things and not

00:30:23.960 --> 00:30:27.820
be always marketing and
packaging it and doing this?

00:30:27.820 --> 00:30:29.670
MEI-MEI ZHAO: I
was going to say.

00:30:29.670 --> 00:30:32.211
RICK SMOLAN: I guess I didn't
listen to that advice too well.

00:30:32.211 --> 00:30:36.030
But it was like going to school.

00:30:36.030 --> 00:30:38.246
And, of course, I
was smitten with her.

00:30:38.246 --> 00:30:38.745
And--

00:30:39.120 --> 00:30:40.870
MEI-MEI ZHAO: And this
blossoming romance.

00:30:40.870 --> 00:30:42.310
RICK SMOLAN: It was
somewhat mutual.

00:30:42.310 --> 00:30:43.976
I think it was probably
more on my side.

00:30:43.976 --> 00:30:46.361
But it was the most
interesting year of my life.

00:30:46.361 --> 00:30:47.860
And we're really
good friends still,

00:30:47.860 --> 00:30:48.730
and we talk all the time.

00:30:48.730 --> 00:30:49.850
The most fun thing
with the movie

00:30:49.850 --> 00:30:51.660
was that I got to
go to Australia when

00:30:51.660 --> 00:30:52.490
the movie came out.

00:30:52.490 --> 00:30:57.060
And the filmmakers put us on
a two-week publicity tour.

00:30:57.060 --> 00:30:58.552
We didn't keep
watching the movie.

00:30:58.552 --> 00:31:00.260
We'd show up at the
end of the screenings

00:31:00.260 --> 00:31:01.551
and do a Q&amp;A with the audience.

00:31:01.551 --> 00:31:04.260
And it was just so much
fun being with her again

00:31:04.260 --> 00:31:06.230
and just comparing
memories, because we

00:31:06.230 --> 00:31:08.690
are very different memories
of some of the trip as well.

00:31:08.690 --> 00:31:09.975
It was just normal.

00:31:09.975 --> 00:31:11.350
MEI-MEI ZHAO: So
part two of this

00:31:11.350 --> 00:31:13.530
is bringing her in and
asking her side of the story.

00:31:13.530 --> 00:31:14.820
RICK SMOLAN: Yeah,
when she's in New York,

00:31:14.820 --> 00:31:16.510
she should come
and visit you guys.

00:31:17.574 --> 00:31:19.240
Just one of the most
interesting people.

00:31:19.240 --> 00:31:23.450
And everything's just
constantly original thinking.

00:31:23.450 --> 00:31:25.680
It comes with things from
a different perspective

00:31:25.680 --> 00:31:27.090
than most people.

00:31:27.090 --> 00:31:29.340
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Now, what is
she doing in New York City?

00:31:30.250 --> 00:31:32.250
RICK SMOLAN: Right now,
she's back in Australia.

00:31:32.250 --> 00:31:34.541
Actually, she's in Bali today
at a writer's conference.

00:31:35.534 --> 00:31:37.450
Remember when we all
read "Catcher in the Rye"

00:31:37.450 --> 00:31:38.844
growing up in school?

00:31:38.844 --> 00:31:40.760
Her book, "Tracks," is
like that in Australia.

00:31:40.760 --> 00:31:42.130
Every school kid reads "Tracks."

00:31:42.130 --> 00:31:44.625
They actually have a
29-page study guide,

00:31:44.625 --> 00:31:46.500
which we're actually
offering with this, too,

00:31:46.500 --> 00:31:47.720
as the Kickstarter
thing, because it's

00:31:47.720 --> 00:31:49.011
sort of very thought-provoking.

00:31:49.011 --> 00:31:50.630
The kids talk
about, what is Robyn

00:31:50.630 --> 00:31:52.010
say about aboriginal rights?

00:31:52.010 --> 00:31:54.640
And why did she want to spend
time with the Aborigines?

00:31:54.640 --> 00:31:56.655
And what was her
relationship with the camels?

00:31:58.310 --> 00:32:00.092
I'll give you one
back story if you're

00:32:00.092 --> 00:32:01.800
going to see the movie
that will actually

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:03.990
make you enjoy the
movie more, which

00:32:03.990 --> 00:32:06.670
is that she had this wonderful
dog with her named Diggity.

00:32:06.670 --> 00:32:09.330
And Diggity saved her life
many times during the trip.

00:32:09.330 --> 00:32:11.860
It was like her daughter, her
companion, her sleeping bag,

00:32:11.860 --> 00:32:12.610
confidant.

00:32:12.610 --> 00:32:14.070
You talk to Diggity
all day long.

00:32:15.290 --> 00:32:18.317
And this is not in the movie.

00:32:18.317 --> 00:32:19.400
It's not even in her book.

00:32:19.400 --> 00:32:21.910
But two years before
the camel trip,

00:32:21.910 --> 00:32:25.181
Robyn was working as a janitor
at a hospital in Brisbane.

00:32:25.181 --> 00:32:27.680
And so she'd come in at night
and clean all the garbage out.

00:32:27.680 --> 00:32:30.470
And she heard these terrible
cries coming from the basement

00:32:30.470 --> 00:32:33.250
and found out that they
were taking animals

00:32:33.250 --> 00:32:34.860
from kill shelters
and using them

00:32:34.860 --> 00:32:37.400
to experiment on dogs and cats.

00:32:37.400 --> 00:32:39.490
And she just said she
couldn't stand it.

00:32:39.490 --> 00:32:41.860
And she waited till
everybody was gone one night

00:32:41.860 --> 00:32:44.430
and came back with the keys
and opened up all the cages,

00:32:44.430 --> 00:32:46.526
opened all the doors, and
let all the animals out.

00:32:46.526 --> 00:32:48.400
And there was one puppy
that had been brought

00:32:48.400 --> 00:32:51.605
in that morning that
didn't run away.

00:32:51.605 --> 00:32:52.480
And that was Diggity.

00:32:52.480 --> 00:32:53.510
That became her dog.

00:32:54.259 --> 00:32:56.050
MEI-MEI ZHAO: I'm
getting a tear in my ear.

00:32:56.050 --> 00:32:57.549
RICK SMOLAN: When
you see the movie,

00:32:57.549 --> 00:32:59.660
that story will
resonate with you.

00:33:00.980 --> 00:33:03.400
Reviewers been saying that
amongst many other things

00:33:03.400 --> 00:33:06.480
about this movie, the
relationship between Robyn

00:33:06.480 --> 00:33:09.380
and her dog is something
you'll never forget.

00:33:09.380 --> 00:33:10.505
It's just extraordinary.

00:33:11.740 --> 00:33:13.546
Anyway, I'm getting
tears in my eyes too.

00:33:14.974 --> 00:33:17.070
MEI-MEI ZHAO: All
right, so that's great.

00:33:17.070 --> 00:33:19.950
I think I'm definitely
going to go see the movie.

00:33:19.950 --> 00:33:20.710
I can't wait.

00:33:20.710 --> 00:33:23.905
And now I think everyone in the
audience feels the same way.

00:33:23.905 --> 00:33:26.889
So I do want to leave some
time to talk about "The Human

00:33:26.889 --> 00:33:29.055
Face of Big Data," which
is a very exciting project.

00:33:31.034 --> 00:33:32.700
Do you mind telling
us a little bit more

00:33:32.700 --> 00:33:34.860
about "The Human
Face of Big Data"?

00:33:34.860 --> 00:33:37.390
I think this would be the
audience who would enjoy it.

00:33:37.390 --> 00:33:38.640
RICK SMOLAN: I'm a TED junkie.

00:33:38.640 --> 00:33:45.310
I love going to TED and other
conferences-- ideacity and EEG.

00:33:45.310 --> 00:33:48.520
And Marissa Mayer,
an old friend--

00:33:48.520 --> 00:33:50.450
I met her at TED
probably 10 years ago.

00:33:50.450 --> 00:33:54.270
And when she was
still at Google,

00:33:54.270 --> 00:33:55.580
we were talking at TED one day.

00:33:55.580 --> 00:33:57.329
And she said, so what's
your next project?

00:33:57.329 --> 00:33:59.950
And I started doing these
geographic projects.

00:33:59.950 --> 00:34:02.320
You know, "One Day in the
Life of America," coming out

00:34:02.320 --> 00:34:04.390
of that first "Life"
assignment or Australia

00:34:04.390 --> 00:34:05.410
or other countries.

00:34:05.410 --> 00:34:07.500
And then I thought, what if
you could take the same idea?

00:34:07.500 --> 00:34:09.375
So the concept of the
"Day in the Life" books

00:34:09.375 --> 00:34:11.510
was I invited my
heroes, my peers,

00:34:11.510 --> 00:34:13.074
and some young
photographers, and we

00:34:13.074 --> 00:34:14.449
would spend months
getting ready.

00:34:14.449 --> 00:34:16.976
But we'd fly them to a country
and we'd say, on your mark,

00:34:16.976 --> 00:34:17.670
get set, go.

00:34:17.670 --> 00:34:19.460
We'd distribute them
around the country

00:34:19.460 --> 00:34:22.774
geographically and thematically
and say, OK, you got 24 hours.

00:34:22.774 --> 00:34:25.190
Again, it got turned down by
every publisher in the world.

00:34:25.190 --> 00:34:26.170
They said, what a stupid idea.

00:34:26.170 --> 00:34:28.794
It's like, who would care about
a bunch of photographers taking

00:34:28.794 --> 00:34:31.232
pictures on a day in
some godforsaken country?

00:34:31.232 --> 00:34:33.190
And it became the
bestselling photography books

00:34:33.190 --> 00:34:33.815
ever published.

00:34:33.815 --> 00:34:35.449
I think we sold
five million copies.

00:34:35.449 --> 00:34:37.530
20,000 was a best seller.

00:34:37.530 --> 00:34:40.239
So I thought, what if we took
that same idea, and instead

00:34:40.239 --> 00:34:43.630
of a geographic sort of random
"what happens in a day," what

00:34:43.630 --> 00:34:46.949
if we did a deep dive on how the
human race is learning to heal

00:34:46.949 --> 00:34:51.159
itself, or the global water
crisis, or-- Marissa's idea

00:34:51.159 --> 00:34:52.699
was, why don't you
look at big data?

00:34:52.699 --> 00:34:53.710
Because I was trying
figure out what to do?

00:34:53.710 --> 00:34:55.112
And I said, what's that?

00:34:55.112 --> 00:34:56.570
And she said, well,
some people say

00:34:56.570 --> 00:34:57.685
it's so much
information it doesn't

00:34:57.685 --> 00:34:58.785
fit in your personal computer.

00:34:58.785 --> 00:35:00.710
And I said, that doesn't
sound very interesting.

00:35:00.710 --> 00:35:02.293
And she said, well,
other people think

00:35:02.293 --> 00:35:04.370
it's overlapping data
sets to find patterns.

00:35:04.370 --> 00:35:08.320
And I said, I'm a photographer
and I don't get it.

00:35:08.320 --> 00:35:10.446
And she said, OK,
a lot of us think

00:35:10.446 --> 00:35:11.820
we're watching
the planet develop

00:35:11.820 --> 00:35:14.430
a rudimentary nervous
system and that all

00:35:14.430 --> 00:35:16.090
of us with our
smartphones are starting

00:35:16.090 --> 00:35:19.030
to become sensors and nodes
on this growing brain.

00:35:19.030 --> 00:35:21.420
And I said, whoa,
say that again.

00:35:21.420 --> 00:35:23.509
And it was such a cool idea.

00:35:23.509 --> 00:35:24.925
So she and her
husband, Zack, came

00:35:24.925 --> 00:35:26.450
and spent a day
with us in New York

00:35:26.450 --> 00:35:28.600
brainstorming how
to do this project.

00:35:28.600 --> 00:35:29.800
She was so generous.

00:35:29.800 --> 00:35:32.140
And the first thing
she pointing me to-- I

00:35:32.140 --> 00:35:35.339
decide Eric Schmidt walking out
as we walked in this morning.

00:35:35.339 --> 00:35:36.880
The first thing
Marissa pointed me to

00:35:36.880 --> 00:35:39.080
was this wonderful
quote of Eric's saying

00:35:39.080 --> 00:35:42.382
that of all the data from the
dawn of humanity to 2003--

00:35:42.382 --> 00:35:44.920
I don't know how he figure
this out-- was five exabytes.

00:35:44.920 --> 00:35:47.960
And now every two
days, the human race

00:35:47.960 --> 00:35:49.200
is generating five exabytes.

00:35:49.200 --> 00:35:51.070
Now, even if you don't know
what an exabyte is, and you all

00:35:51.070 --> 00:35:52.690
do but I didn't
at the time-- I'm

00:35:52.690 --> 00:35:55.390
still not quite sure I
do-- the fact that we're

00:35:55.390 --> 00:35:58.460
seeing a straight vertical
line is unbelievable.

00:35:58.460 --> 00:36:03.485
She also told me
that the first day

00:36:03.485 --> 00:36:05.609
of a baby's life,
the human race is now

00:36:05.609 --> 00:36:07.900
generating 70 times the amount
of information contained

00:36:07.900 --> 00:36:12.110
in the Library of Congress
and that people walking

00:36:12.110 --> 00:36:14.880
through Times Square are exposed
to as much information in one

00:36:14.880 --> 00:36:17.220
day as our ancestors
from the 15th century

00:36:17.220 --> 00:36:19.240
were exposed to in
their entire life.

00:36:19.240 --> 00:36:21.360
So in every one of these, we're
seeing a straight vertical line

00:36:21.360 --> 00:36:23.276
that's unlike anything
we've ever seen before.

00:36:23.276 --> 00:36:25.541
So we figured, well, how
do you photograph that?

00:36:25.541 --> 00:36:27.540
I mean, it's very
interesting, and these are all

00:36:27.540 --> 00:36:28.530
great statistics.

00:36:28.530 --> 00:36:35.530
So we did this book called
"The Human Face of Big Data."

00:36:35.530 --> 00:36:37.480
And it's actually
remarkably human.

00:36:37.480 --> 00:36:39.460
I'm just going to
open it anywhere.

00:36:39.460 --> 00:36:42.650
And let's see if I can
find a story to give you.

00:36:42.650 --> 00:36:43.900
And here's an example.

00:36:43.900 --> 00:36:46.984
This is our Google
graphic that opened nicely

00:36:46.984 --> 00:36:49.400
in the right place of all the
different arms and tentacles

00:36:49.400 --> 00:36:50.900
of Google and all
the different ways

00:36:50.900 --> 00:36:53.645
that your technologies
affect the world.

00:36:54.890 --> 00:36:56.600
But there was a
really cool story.

00:36:57.650 --> 00:37:00.060
Remember the earthquake
about five years ago?

00:37:00.060 --> 00:37:01.492
This terrible earthquake.

00:37:01.492 --> 00:37:03.700
And we're all talking about
the terrible destruction.

00:37:03.700 --> 00:37:07.150
And I was listening to Kai
Ryssdal on National Public

00:37:07.150 --> 00:37:09.650
Radio on "Marketplace," and
he was the only reporter

00:37:09.650 --> 00:37:11.215
that talked about
that earthquake.

00:37:11.215 --> 00:37:12.920
And he told us a
story-- I think it

00:37:12.920 --> 00:37:14.710
was Steve Henn
was the reporter--

00:37:14.710 --> 00:37:18.150
and said that 15 seconds
before the earthquake hit,

00:37:18.150 --> 00:37:20.750
before the earthquake
hit, that every bullet

00:37:20.750 --> 00:37:23.315
train, every factory in Japan
came to a halt, actually

00:37:23.315 --> 00:37:23.815
stopped.

00:37:24.920 --> 00:37:27.464
And they had put an early
warning system all over Japan.

00:37:27.464 --> 00:37:29.380
I'm trying to find the
picture here somewhere.

00:37:30.535 --> 00:37:31.370
I want to find it.

00:37:31.370 --> 00:37:34.820
But they found that they
could actually put sensors

00:37:34.820 --> 00:37:37.360
all over Japan that would
sense this P-wave that

00:37:37.360 --> 00:37:40.030
became before the wave that was
actually the destructive wave.

00:37:40.030 --> 00:37:41.310
And I thought, that's so cool.

00:37:41.310 --> 00:37:42.990
They use these data centers.

00:37:42.990 --> 00:37:45.950
But then I found out there's a
group of guys in Palo Alto that

00:37:45.950 --> 00:37:49.140
realized that all of our
laptops have accelerometers

00:37:49.140 --> 00:37:50.150
in them down.

00:37:50.150 --> 00:37:52.250
And they wrote a program
called Quake-Catcher.

00:37:52.250 --> 00:37:53.960
So before people
go to bed at night,

00:37:53.960 --> 00:37:56.610
they fire up Quake-Catcher,
and they just leave it running.

00:37:56.610 --> 00:37:59.370
And it actually is this
low-cost, ubiquitous,

00:37:59.370 --> 00:38:01.580
completely free early
earthquake warning

00:38:01.580 --> 00:38:03.990
system, which is amazing.

00:38:03.990 --> 00:38:06.680
So the whole book is full
of stories like that.

00:38:06.680 --> 00:38:07.527
There's a group--

00:38:07.527 --> 00:38:08.860
MEI-MEI ZHAO: "A Day in a Life."

00:38:08.860 --> 00:38:09.610
RICK SMOLAN: Yeah.

00:38:09.610 --> 00:38:13.490
It's sort of how we're starting
to be able to understand cause

00:38:13.490 --> 00:38:16.050
and effect in real time
in a way that we've never

00:38:16.050 --> 00:38:18.070
been able to as
a species before.

00:38:18.070 --> 00:38:21.190
An we put Eric's quote as
the opening page of the book.

00:38:21.190 --> 00:38:24.000
MEI-MEI ZHAO: There's a quote
in here by Albert Einstein.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:26.130
"Not everything that
can be counted counts

00:38:26.130 --> 00:38:28.542
and not everything that
counts can be counted."

00:38:28.542 --> 00:38:29.250
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

00:38:29.250 --> 00:38:30.992
[LAUGHING]

00:38:30.992 --> 00:38:32.700
RICK SMOLAN: It's very
thought-provoking.

00:38:32.700 --> 00:38:34.491
MEI-MEI ZHAO: It takes
a moment to process.

00:38:34.972 --> 00:38:35.930
This is really amazing.

00:38:35.930 --> 00:38:37.300
RICK SMOLAN: We had some
wonderful essays in it.

00:38:37.300 --> 00:38:40.060
But it sounds like, well,
what would you photograph?

00:38:40.060 --> 00:38:42.761
Like the Google data
servers with lights

00:38:42.761 --> 00:38:44.010
blinking on them or something?

00:38:44.010 --> 00:38:46.346
But it actually is
very, very human.

00:38:46.346 --> 00:38:47.720
All the stories
in here-- we want

00:38:47.720 --> 00:38:49.095
to put stories
where you couldn't

00:38:49.095 --> 00:38:51.509
wait to tell your
friends, you've

00:38:51.509 --> 00:38:52.550
got to look at the story.

00:38:52.550 --> 00:38:53.570
It's so compelling.

00:38:53.570 --> 00:38:54.640
Here, I'll give you one example.

00:38:54.640 --> 00:38:56.098
I know we're probably
running late.

00:38:56.098 --> 00:38:59.890
But there's a guy named Shwetak
Patel, who's 28 years old,

00:38:59.890 --> 00:39:02.490
and this is his third startup.

00:39:02.490 --> 00:39:05.050
And he said, imagine if you
got your America Express credit

00:39:05.050 --> 00:39:07.150
card tomorrow, and there
was no itemization.

00:39:07.150 --> 00:39:09.630
Would you pay your credit
card if it break down

00:39:09.630 --> 00:39:11.150
what you spent your money on?

00:39:11.150 --> 00:39:13.520
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Some months
it might be better that way.

00:39:13.520 --> 00:39:14.750
RICK SMOLAN: But
most people wouldn't.

00:39:14.750 --> 00:39:16.550
And yet, we get an
electrical bill every month,

00:39:16.550 --> 00:39:18.758
and we have no idea what
we're spending our money on.

00:39:18.758 --> 00:39:21.420
So he invented a little gadget,
which he just sold the Belkin.

00:39:21.420 --> 00:39:23.240
You plug it in
anywhere in your house,

00:39:23.240 --> 00:39:26.580
and it'll give you literally
a read-out by device

00:39:26.580 --> 00:39:27.330
in your house.

00:39:28.235 --> 00:39:30.610
Every device doesn't have to
be plugged into this gadget.

00:39:30.610 --> 00:39:32.193
You just plug it in
once in the house,

00:39:32.193 --> 00:39:35.610
and it recognizes the digital
signature of every appliance.

00:39:35.610 --> 00:39:37.559
And so now he can show
you what you spent.

00:39:37.559 --> 00:39:39.100
And I said, well,
that's pretty cool,

00:39:39.100 --> 00:39:41.365
but you still have
to pay the bill.

00:39:41.365 --> 00:39:42.700
And he said, yeah.

00:39:42.700 --> 00:39:45.800
I said, but did
you get an insight

00:39:45.800 --> 00:39:48.037
from this data that makes
you change your behavior?

00:39:48.037 --> 00:39:50.120
And he thought about it
for a minute, and he said,

00:39:50.120 --> 00:39:50.703
you know what?

00:39:50.703 --> 00:39:52.740
We actually found that
the average American

00:39:52.740 --> 00:39:57.210
spends 11% of their monthly
electric bill on their DVR

00:39:57.210 --> 00:39:59.660
that these devices weren't
designed to spin down.

00:39:59.660 --> 00:40:02.590
So if you only record "The
Blacklist" on Monday night,

00:40:02.590 --> 00:40:04.830
and the rest of the week
it's sitting there not

00:40:04.830 --> 00:40:07.020
doing anything, it's
still spinning away.

00:40:07.020 --> 00:40:10.340
So maybe we could lower
America's energy consumption

00:40:10.340 --> 00:40:12.630
by just redesigning
the damn DVR.

00:40:12.630 --> 00:40:14.380
So there's these
wonderful little insights

00:40:14.380 --> 00:40:17.580
like that that came
out of the book.

00:40:17.580 --> 00:40:18.770
Can I give you one last one?

00:40:18.770 --> 00:40:19.520
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Yeah, of course.

00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:22.190
RICK SMOLAN: There's a company
in Boston called Ginger.io that

00:40:22.190 --> 00:40:25.300
can predict you're going to get
depressed two days before you

00:40:25.300 --> 00:40:27.495
get depressed, before you
show any outward signs

00:40:27.495 --> 00:40:28.344
of depression.

00:40:28.344 --> 00:40:30.760
So I said, well, first of all,
that sounded kind of wacky.

00:40:30.760 --> 00:40:34.114
And I also said, why
would you want to do that?

00:40:34.114 --> 00:40:35.530
And he said, well,
actually, we're

00:40:35.530 --> 00:40:36.870
using it for medical purposes.

00:40:36.870 --> 00:40:40.010
He said that people
with diabetes

00:40:40.010 --> 00:40:42.432
apparently have very high
correlation with depression.

00:40:42.432 --> 00:40:43.890
And when people
get depressed, they

00:40:43.890 --> 00:40:45.060
stop taking their medicine.

00:40:45.060 --> 00:40:47.640
And if you have diabetes,
you don't take your medicine,

00:40:47.640 --> 00:40:49.470
there's very dire consequences.

00:40:49.470 --> 00:40:50.980
So he said, we have this app.

00:40:50.980 --> 00:40:51.897
It's called Ginger.io.

00:40:51.897 --> 00:40:54.438
And basically, you install it
on your Android phone, your iOS

00:40:54.438 --> 00:40:55.010
phone.

00:40:55.010 --> 00:40:58.190
And it basically
creates a baseline

00:40:58.190 --> 00:40:59.980
of what's normal for you.

00:40:59.980 --> 00:41:02.330
And then two days before
you're showing any outward sign

00:41:02.330 --> 00:41:05.710
of depression-- there's
20 different data points,

00:41:05.710 --> 00:41:09.300
but it says your tweets and
emails and text are going down.

00:41:09.300 --> 00:41:11.240
The amount of time you
spend at home goes up.

00:41:11.240 --> 00:41:13.035
I mean, it has all
these different ways

00:41:13.035 --> 00:41:14.035
of looking at a pattern.

00:41:14.035 --> 00:41:16.160
I said, well, wouldn't that
just mean you're getting sick?

00:41:16.160 --> 00:41:17.576
He said, no, we
have other things.

00:41:17.576 --> 00:41:20.245
And he said, people actually
put this on their own phone.

00:41:20.245 --> 00:41:21.620
And it says, if
it looks like I'm

00:41:21.620 --> 00:41:23.950
going into one of those
terrible deep depressions,

00:41:23.950 --> 00:41:27.350
call my neighbor or my doctor
or my brother or my sister,

00:41:27.350 --> 00:41:30.066
whatever, just to make sure that
somebody checks in with them.

00:41:30.066 --> 00:41:31.440
So again it's sort
of like-- they

00:41:31.440 --> 00:41:32.920
call it the nurse
in your pocket.

00:41:34.120 --> 00:41:36.740
And a lot of the new
medical applications

00:41:36.740 --> 00:41:38.520
that you guys are
looking at Google

00:41:38.520 --> 00:41:40.853
are using these sort of devices
that we're all carrying.

00:41:41.840 --> 00:41:43.840
Some people get creeped
out by, and other people

00:41:43.840 --> 00:41:44.880
think this is so cool.

00:41:44.880 --> 00:41:48.180
It's a way of looking at
your life from 30,000 feet

00:41:48.180 --> 00:41:49.690
and seeing the
pattern of your life.

00:41:49.690 --> 00:41:50.410
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Yeah, definitely.

00:41:50.410 --> 00:41:51.690
I see that you're
wearing a Jawbone there.

00:41:51.690 --> 00:41:52.140
I have one as well--

00:41:52.140 --> 00:41:52.570
RICK SMOLAN: Yeah, I love this.

00:41:52.570 --> 00:41:53.210
MEI-MEI ZHAO: --that
I'm not sporting.

00:41:53.210 --> 00:41:55.597
But yeah, personalized data,
making informed decisions

00:41:55.597 --> 00:41:56.930
with data is really [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:56.930 --> 00:41:58.888
RICK SMOLAN: I was
surprised that the new Apple

