00:42:58.240 --> 00:42:59.198
at Google the same way.

00:43:00.750 --> 00:43:03.010
I always remember the
stories of Larry and Sergey.

00:43:03.010 --> 00:43:04.622
So I'm going from
college to Google.

00:43:04.622 --> 00:43:06.330
And when I visited
Google the first time,

00:43:06.330 --> 00:43:07.746
it felt like a big
college campus.

00:43:09.220 --> 00:43:13.380
The thing that I love about
organizations like Google

00:43:13.380 --> 00:43:16.970
is this idea of collisions,
this idea that you build

00:43:16.970 --> 00:43:19.360
a facility where people run
into each other by accident.

00:43:19.360 --> 00:43:22.040
And you overhear somebody
at the water cooler.

00:43:22.040 --> 00:43:24.264
Or you're in a room
where suddenly a problem

00:43:24.264 --> 00:43:26.680
you're trying to solve, you
run into just the right person

00:43:26.680 --> 00:43:29.600
at the right time, because
the facility is designed

00:43:29.600 --> 00:43:31.265
to allow those random meetings.

00:43:32.450 --> 00:43:33.450
MEI-MEI ZHAO: Fantastic.

00:43:34.902 --> 00:43:35.813
Yes.

00:43:35.813 --> 00:43:36.354
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:43:36.354 --> 00:43:39.079
So a problem that I'm
guessing you run into a lot--

00:43:39.079 --> 00:43:41.120
and you told us a story
about running into this--

00:43:41.120 --> 00:43:43.530
is a lot of times
people don't like

00:43:43.530 --> 00:43:44.780
to get their picture taken.

00:43:44.780 --> 00:43:46.840
So I'm wondering
how you approach

00:43:46.840 --> 00:43:49.540
this when you're taking pictures
of strangers, how you handle

00:43:49.540 --> 00:43:51.849
that and get them OK with
you taking their picture?

00:43:51.849 --> 00:43:53.640
RICK SMOLAN: That's a
really good question.

00:43:53.640 --> 00:43:55.650
And, oddly enough, I
find that most people--

00:43:55.650 --> 00:43:56.400
[RINGTONE CHIMING]

00:43:56.400 --> 00:43:56.920
I'm sorry.

00:43:57.980 --> 00:44:02.862
I turned the sound on so you
could hear the videos working.

00:44:02.862 --> 00:44:04.600
I actually find
most people don't

00:44:04.600 --> 00:44:07.180
mind being photographed
as long as you

00:44:07.180 --> 00:44:09.350
are comfortable
photographing them.

00:44:09.350 --> 00:44:12.330
If you're taking a picture
sneakily of somebody

00:44:12.330 --> 00:44:13.990
or-- I find the
people that get upset

00:44:13.990 --> 00:44:16.960
are usually the ones that feel
like you're making fun of them.

00:44:16.960 --> 00:44:19.562
So the one thing that my
wiser, older friends told me

00:44:19.562 --> 00:44:21.395
when I was getting
started as a photographer

00:44:21.395 --> 00:44:24.290
is if people get upset,
always walk over to them

00:44:24.290 --> 00:44:27.500
and apologize and tell them why
you were taking the picture.

00:44:28.640 --> 00:44:30.430
You look just like
my grandmother,

00:44:30.430 --> 00:44:32.950
or I love the light on
you, or I'm a photographer,

00:44:32.950 --> 00:44:33.999
and I'm sorry.

00:44:33.999 --> 00:44:35.290
I didn't need to get you upset.

00:44:35.290 --> 00:44:37.760
And 99% of the
time, people are--

00:44:37.760 --> 00:44:40.670
as long as you don't
slunk away like you just

00:44:40.670 --> 00:44:42.210
did something bad, they're fine.

00:44:42.210 --> 00:44:44.780
It's so funny how
your being confident

00:44:44.780 --> 00:44:46.197
makes them feel comfortable.

00:44:46.197 --> 00:44:47.780
A lot of times,
especially when you're

00:44:47.780 --> 00:44:50.113
working in countries where
you don't speak the language,

00:44:50.113 --> 00:44:52.750
just making eye contact and
smiling and saying-- you

00:44:52.750 --> 00:44:55.144
get really good
at sign language.

00:44:55.144 --> 00:44:56.560
And sometimes
people do get upset.

00:44:56.560 --> 00:44:59.445
I find-- this is my
bad generalization.

00:44:59.445 --> 00:45:01.992
I'm sure somebody who's
watching this afterwards

00:45:01.992 --> 00:45:03.200
will write me a nasty letter.

00:45:03.200 --> 00:45:05.012
But I find that a
lot of times when

00:45:05.012 --> 00:45:06.700
people don't like
being photographed,

00:45:06.700 --> 00:45:10.500
it's because they have a
negative opinion of themselves.

00:45:10.500 --> 00:45:13.430
They've been made fun of,
or they're feeling somehow

00:45:13.430 --> 00:45:16.440
your taking a picture of them
is ridiculing in some way.

00:45:16.440 --> 00:45:18.310
And mostly when I
photograph people,

00:45:18.310 --> 00:45:20.490
it's because I find
them or where they are

00:45:20.490 --> 00:45:22.100
or what's happening interesting.

00:45:22.100 --> 00:45:23.760
I don't know if that answers
your question or not.

00:45:23.760 --> 00:45:24.210
AUDIENCE: Yeah, definitely.

