00:48:30.840 --> 00:48:33.010
and we all incorporate it into
our PowerPoint presentations

00:48:33.010 --> 00:48:33.580
in Keynote.

00:48:36.960 --> 00:48:40.549
If you see the movie,
I do the opposite

00:48:40.549 --> 00:48:41.840
of what Adam does in the movie.

00:48:41.840 --> 00:48:45.460
Adam is in her face saying,
do this, do that, turn here,

00:48:45.460 --> 00:48:46.780
and do that.

00:48:46.780 --> 00:48:49.310
I actually kind of
disappear into the woodwork.

00:48:49.310 --> 00:48:52.800
When I photograph
people, they get board.

00:48:52.800 --> 00:48:54.820
I mean, I want them to.

00:48:54.820 --> 00:48:56.490
I want them to forget
I'm even there.

00:48:56.490 --> 00:48:57.417
It's really hard.

00:48:57.417 --> 00:48:59.000
You know how we all
have a photo face?

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:01.680
When somebody has
a camera, we have

00:49:01.680 --> 00:49:03.710
the same look that we all have.

00:49:03.710 --> 00:49:06.810
But if somebody actually spent
a week photographing you,

00:49:06.810 --> 00:49:09.170
they would get the real you,
because eventually you'd

00:49:09.170 --> 00:49:10.836
just go back to what
you're going to do,

00:49:10.836 --> 00:49:13.740
because you just can't
keep the photo face on.

00:49:13.740 --> 00:49:16.210
And so I always felt
like the pictures

00:49:16.210 --> 00:49:18.760
I took of Robyn and Natasha
and my best pictures were

00:49:18.760 --> 00:49:21.680
when people just literally
forgot I was there.

00:49:21.680 --> 00:49:23.790
I mean, I don't
know if I'm boring.

00:49:23.790 --> 00:49:26.414
But I'm pretty quiet.

00:49:26.414 --> 00:49:28.080
You wouldn't believe
that for this talk.

00:49:29.600 --> 00:49:34.267
And Olivia, who sort of runs
my life now as my assistant,

00:49:34.267 --> 00:49:35.350
doesn't believe I'm quiet.

00:49:35.350 --> 00:49:39.100
But anyway, when
I'm shooting, I try

00:49:39.100 --> 00:49:41.560
to blend into the wallpaper.

00:49:41.560 --> 00:49:44.460
And I figured that I
think that's a secret

00:49:44.460 --> 00:49:46.990
that most people-- they take
the picture and they leave.

00:49:46.990 --> 00:49:48.610
It's sort of fly-by photography.

00:49:48.610 --> 00:49:51.380
And I had the luxury
as a photographer

00:49:51.380 --> 00:49:53.619
of spending a lot
of time with people.

00:49:53.619 --> 00:49:55.160
Even when I got a
one-day assignment,

00:49:55.160 --> 00:49:56.734
if the person I
was photographing

00:49:56.734 --> 00:49:59.150
would let me stay there, I
would spend three or four days.

00:49:59.150 --> 00:50:00.680
The magazine wouldn't
pay me for it,

00:50:00.680 --> 00:50:02.554
but I just felt like I
would do a better job.

00:50:02.554 --> 00:50:04.252
So I would always
over-deliver, and I

00:50:04.252 --> 00:50:05.835
think that's why I
kept getting hired.

00:50:07.039 --> 00:50:08.580
So I don't know if
that helps or not.

00:50:08.580 --> 00:50:09.460
AUDIENCE: No, that's good.

00:50:09.460 --> 00:50:09.960
